<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1915-12-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1915-12-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="607" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d607">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72/2347½</note>
                            <head>
                                <hi rend="italic">President <persName type="from">Wilson</persName>
                                    to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                                </hi>
                            </head>
                            <opener>
                                <dateline rendition="#right">
                                    <placeName>
                                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1915-12-05">
                                        <hi rend="italic">5 December, 1915</hi>.</date>
                                </dateline>
                            </opener>
                            <p>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. Secretary</hi>: This is a most
                                interesting letter,<note n="1" xml:id="d607fn1">
                                    <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_642">p.
                                    642</ref>.</note> and it seems to me that many very significant
                                inferences may be drawn from it as to the state of affairs in the
                                Central Monarchies!</p>
                            <p>Faithfully Yours,</p>
                            <closer>
                                <signed>W. W.</signed>
                            </closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>